">priorities. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In this paper</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for the Northern Ireland Affairs Committee inquiry into the banking structure in NI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we will outline how we have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consumer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">produce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a complete manifesto for day to day banking in NI, alongside three current issues which are impacting on consumers.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.39pt; padding-left:2.61pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Access to financial services</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">B.   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Branch closures</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The payments crisis of 2012</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the role of the Financial Conduct Authority</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have recently published a number of reports on consumer banking from our research with NI consumers as follows:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Personal Current Account Manifesto: A report on issues in daily banking services that consumers want to see improve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d. (As mentioned above- Appendix A)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Access to Branch Banking: Information for the NI Assembly Committee for Finance and Personnel on the impact </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of branch closures on consumers (Appendix B)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Payment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Pending: A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> report into the Ulster Bank payments crisis during summer 2012. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Appendix C)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ways to Pay: A report into cons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">umers’ views on making payments (Appendix D)</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have attached</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> electronic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">copies of these reports with our submission.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have been working with all of the banks operating in Northern Ireland to explain w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hat consumers want</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. We have seen some improvements, however there is more work to be done to improve serv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ices, such as access to services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, boosting confidence in online banking, transparency of information in relation to terms and condition, fees and charges, making complaints and switching bank accounts.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">The role of the Consumer Council in Northern Ireland</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Consumer Council is an independent consumer organisation, working to bring about change to benefit Northern Ireland’s consumers. Our aim is to make the consumer voice heard and make it count. We also have responsibility to educate consumers on their rights and responsibilities and to equip them with the skills they need to make good decisions about their money and manage it wisely.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Consumer Council leads the Financial Capability Partnership NI which brings together Government, banks, building societies, credit unions, education, community and voluntary sectors to ensure that we all help consumers in NI to manage their money and make it work best for them.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The overall vision of the Partnership is: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Together create more financially capable people in Northern Ireland and be able to measure change.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have been working with Government and other stakeholders including banks and building societies to ensure financial services and products are suitable for consumers. Through partnership, we drive change and ensure that consumers are at the centre of policies and decisions.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2004 the Consumer Council and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">Which?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> took a super-complaint against the big four</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> NI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> banks - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ulster Bank, Northern Bank</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (now Danske Bank)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, Bank of Ir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eland and First Trust Bank,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> because evidence suggested</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> consumers weren’t getting a fair deal. The super-complaint led to a Competition Commission investigation which concluded that ba</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nk customers in NI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> were not being offered competitive personal current accounts (PCAs) and that the banks would have to change.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Competition Commission set out a list of legally binding remedies in February 2008 for the banks to implement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, known as the NI Banking Order</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The Consumer Council welcomed these changes as consumers were given the information they needed to take control of their banking and to switch banks to get the best deal possible.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Personal Current accounts in the UK</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The report from the OFT in January 2013 on Personal Current Accounts (PCAs) shows the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re is still a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> need for NI Banks to do more for consumers in NI. It highlights that despite key recommendations made in an OFT market study report into personal current accounts undertaken in 2008, banks continue to drag their heels on implementing more transparency and removing barriers to switching banks, causing ongoing detriment to consumers and ‘major impediment’ to effective competition.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Som</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e progress has been made</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, for example reduction of charges, how information is displayed and the provision of an annual summary which shows how much you have paid in fees and charges over the year. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he OFT report indicates that less than four per cent of consumers across the UK switch bank accounts. Five years after the OFT made key recommendations to banks, there remains a distinct lack of transparency in the cost of current accounts which contributes to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> consumers having a lack of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">confidence in switching banks. A lack of competition, diversity of choice, good value and service also adds to consumer apathy.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is some good news for consumers however. Due to pressure from OFT, FSA and consumer bodies, there has been a significant decrease in unauthorised overdraft charges. However, very few PCA providers offer consumers the ability to opt out of unarranged lending with non-fee carrying personal current accounts.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The OFT report is clear that more needs to be done to give consumers a fairer deal and that banks should be working harder to rebuild confidence in the banking system. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Personal Current Account Manifesto for NI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">( See appendix A)</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Over the past number of years the Consumer Council has carried out extensive research into how consumers view financial products and services in Northern Ireland, how they shop around for products and understand products. The Consumer Council wants to help ensure that consumers are confident that they are getting value for money from their bank and that they are willing to switch if not.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Consumer Council has responded to consumer need by developing a Personal Current Account Manifesto which was informed by consumers who told us that some of the most important things in daily banking are good customer service, clear and transparent charges, easy to understand communications and reliable help when switching from another bank.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have been working with the banks across NI encouraging them to adopt and implement this Manifesto in the interest of consumers. The main recommendations in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the report ask banks to improve the following</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:MuseoSans-300; font-size:12pt">• </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All consumers should be able to open a bank account unless they have a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">criminal conviction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that prevents them from doing s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">• Branches should have opening hours to suit consumers and provide a full</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">range of services.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">• Staff should be involved in training programmes to deal with every</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eventuality and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be empowered to make decisions to help consumers quickly.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">• Fees and charges should be transparent, fair and proportionate.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">• Better communication around how consumers are protected online and training to use these services are vital.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">• Contacting the bank should cost the same for new and existing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">customers. More detail is needed on how much it costs to call using</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">different networks.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">• Communications should be in plain English. More work is needed to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">revise how </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">changes to products can be more easily communicated whilst remaining within the guidelines from the financial regulator.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">• Product offerings should be presented in a way that helps consumers compare the full range of services and know that they can switch.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">• The complaints process should be available from all points of contact,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">verbal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">complaints logged and actioned and leaflets available in branch displays.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">• A review of packaged accounts, eligibility processes and usage of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">individual </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">services is needed.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34pt; padding-left:2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Access</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> to financial services</span></li></ol><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Northern Ireland has the highest pe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rcentage of unbanked households</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the UK. </span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 13 per cent of households</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> here do not have an account which allows money to be paid in and direct debits </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to be paid out, compared to seven</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> per cent in the UK as a whole. Consumers who do not manage their day to day money using a bank account miss out on the convenience of having a choice of ways to pay </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(See Appendix D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and as a result may pay more or miss out on opportunities to save money. For example paying electricity and gas bills by direct debit generally enables consumers to make a saving. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One key target group that we have researched is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">offenders and the role of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> bank accounts for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Having access to a bank account is an essential part of daily life to enable people to set up a home, pay rent and utility bills and receive benefits and wages. Currently none of the banks in NI operate an account opening process for prisoners pending release. We are looking for all banks in NI to provide this service to assist in the resettlement of offenders back into the community. We have been asking the banks and their representative – the British Bankers Association (BBA) for a process to do this for over a year, since our report</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> was published in June 2012.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For consumers with bank accounts, there are still issues getting access to their cash free of charge in certain areas. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We call on the banks and other providers to continue to consider installing more free to use cash machines into deprived areas of Northern Ireland and to maintain existing facilities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The outstanding areas to tackle are Newry, South Armagh, Craigavon and Pomeroy.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Switching bank account</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are pleased that the Payments Council is launching a new guaranteed account switching service in September 2013. We believe there is a need for a clear and guaranteed switching service for current accounts which gives consumers the confidence to switch. The new service should help stimulate competition in the local market if the banks can come up with differentiated products to attract consumers. OFT figures (Jan 2013) indicate that less than four per cent of consumers across the UK switch bank accounts. There is now an opportunity to improve this.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Consumer Council has carried out research into the reasons why consumers here choose certain bank accounts, why they stick with them and what they think is missing.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The main reasons that consumers tell us they haven’t changed bank account are: </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Family loyalty- been with the bank for a long time; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Apathy- all of the banks appear to offer the same thing and there is no differentiation, therefore consumers have no desire to switch as they cannot see the benefits.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Fear that direct debits and other payments will go astray and make them incur charges.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are a number of things that the regulator and the banks could do to help consumers become better equipped when choosing financial products. Common terminology should be used by all banks to make products easier to compare against competitors; banks should make the terms and conditions easy to read, legible font size and more attractive, to encourage more consumers to check them carefully before signing up to products; and overdraft </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fees should be transparent, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">proportionate.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We hope local banks will develop and market compelling product offerings to encourage switching. Offerings must be presented in a way that consumers are able to easily compare the product features and service and know if they will get a better deal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34pt; padding-left:2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Branch c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">losures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> (See Appendix B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">)</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With 53</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> bank branch closures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (see list below) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">during the past two years and further closures on the horizon, the Consumer Council is concerned about the level of access that consumers will have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in order</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to carry out daily banking activities in Northern Ireland.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The number of branches of big 4 banks have reduced from 252 to 199 (21%) in the last 2 year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This matter affects all consumers, regardless of the bank they use. Rural areas appear to be particularly affected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our research shows</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (March 2013) that despite the number of banking services that are provided via telephone and online, branch usage is still high. A sizeable proporti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on of people in NI say they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are still using branches on a regular basis.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">People in Northern Ireland have told us they use branches of banks quite regularly. Eight in ten (80%) visited a branch of a bank at least once in the past year, six in ten (60%) in the last month and three in ten (32%) in the last week.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In reviewing the effectiveness of branch networks, banks should consider the impact that a closure could have on customers who are not able to use online or phone services. Banks should offer to provide a face to face support meeting with consumers who will have to use alternative services such as the Post Office.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Banks should offer basic current account facilities in Post Offices. Co-operation with Post Office Ltd should be continued and consumers informed and encouraged to use facilities at their local post office when this is convenient for them. Not all of the banks offer a full range of services at the Post Office, for example, many do no not offer cash or cheque deposit facilities. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is concern that banks are closing in smaller towns and rural areas, leaving people reliant on branch services at a disadvantage. Consumers on lower incomes or those who are not able to use telephone and internet banking could be affected financially. Having to travel further to avail of services could mean that opportunities for consumers to make their money</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">go further are restricted</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We gave evidence to the Finance and Personnel Committee at the NI Assembly on the 10 July 2013 at an extraordi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nary meeting called to explore Ulster Bank’s announcement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that more branches would be earmarked for closure in the near future. It is apparent from our discussions with MLAs that they are concerned for their constituents who may either be unable to travel to an alternative branch or have the skills or confidence to use online or telephone banking. The Consumer Council will be carrying out further research on the impact of bank closures this year. This covers all banks operating in NI. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The following is a list of all known branches that have closed in 2012 and are closing in 2013.</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; float:left; margin:0pt 9pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Bank of Ireland</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; bo