iam, Belfast</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Larne</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Limavady</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Holywood </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Stormont, Belfast</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ardglass sub office</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Carryduff</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Dromore, Co.Tyrone</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Harryville</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Jordanstown</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Knock, Belfast</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Longstone Street- …..Lisburn</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Moy sub office</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Rosslea sub office</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Saintfield sub office</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Shaftesbury Square …Belfast</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:110pt"><tr style="height:15pt"><td style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:bottom; width:110pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34pt; padding-left:2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The payments crisis in 2012</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> and the role of the Financial Conduct Authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> (See Appendix C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">)</span></li></ol><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Consumer Council represented consumers during summer 2012 when the Ulster Bank payments systems failed. We set out a number of recommendations in our report ‘Payment Pending</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’ to demonstrate to service providers and the financial regulator what customers expect in the handling of a crisis and the assurances required to restore trust. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The major problem that led to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">long term </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">collapse of the system for NI consumers was that the IT infrastructure was built in such a way that issues had to be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fully</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> resolv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed for both Natwest and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> RBS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> customers, before finally turning attention to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Ulster Bank. As a result consumers in NI became third class customers and endured multiple weeks of being unable to access accounts.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">The role of the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA)</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Previously the Financial Services Authority (FSA) supervision policy allowed for increased scrutiny of the largest firms with the largest number of customers across the UK. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This meant that not all banks operating in NI were receiving the same robust and persistent supervision.   We are expecting to see a more detailed level of testing extended to NI now that FCA has taken up its new role.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">More than a year on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from the payments crisis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in June 2012 the financial regulator, the UK Financial Conduct Authority is yet to make a public determination on the payments crisis issue. In May 2013 the FCA announced its intention to conduct an enforcement investigation on this matter.  The Consumer Council held a meeting with senior FCA staff on Thursday 4 July 2013 on behalf of NI consumers. We raised concerns at the lack of clarity from FCA as to whether it will publish a report on the findings of its investigation into RBS, including Ulster Bank, the lack of communication with NI consumers to date and the lack of confidence resulting from that limited information to date. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Consumer Council has advised that to help rebuild consumer confidence in the banking system, and regulation of the banking system, it is vital that there is openness and transparency from the regulator. Consumers expect reports examining the cause and impact of emerging problems, such as the payments crisis which had a prolonged impact, to be timely and made available publically. Crucially, the fundamental questions that remain for consumers and actions put in place to address them must be provided to give the necessary assurances and confidence going forward.  Alongside this, we have asked the FCA for more transparency in relation to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">asking</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> firms to be more clear and straightforward</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in how they provide product and contractual information to consumers and providing information to us on the consumer issues they investigate.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We are disappointed to receive a letter on 19 August 2013 to state that the details of the independent report into the IT </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">payments failure of RBS/Ulster B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ank will not be published.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Areas the committee could consider further</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Structure and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Regulation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> of banks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With no information available from the FCA on the IT structures that banks have in place, it would be comforting for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NI consumers to know that there is not a hierarchy that would prevent them from receiving the same speed and quality of service as consumers in GB, should a problem </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or changes to products </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">arise.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> How do the FCA and banks plan to communicate to consumers how they are dealing with concerns in light of the payments crisis of 2012?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">How can consumers be assured</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that the FCA are taking necessary steps following the payments crisis in 2012 following their decision to not publis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h a report or any information on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> their work to date.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Branch closures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Are banks considering any further branch closures and if so how will they work with consumers to ensure they are still able to acce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ss vital daily banking services?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Do banks making individual commercial deci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">si</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ons on branch closures asses the impact of overall aces to banking services in the local areas? How can this be addressed from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consumer focused</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> holistic approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Credit unions:</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is an increasing reliance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on the services of credit unions in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local communities. Although, due to their nature, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> most do not offer the same range of daily banking services as banks, such as cheque books, direct debits, cash machines and online statements.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Should credit unions be supported to help consumers become more financially included?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> If so, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">how</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This paper has outlined the key issues which are currently impacting on consumers and their day to day banking. These areas, alongside financial capability and helping consumers manage their money, must be addressed to ensure banking services are fair, transparent and responsive to consumer needs. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Family Resources Survey 2010/11 published on 8 February 2013.  Department for Social Development.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Financial capability for offenders, their families and victims. The Consumer Council. June 2012.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">  Data: Ipsos Mori 5-19 March 2013, 1003 participants.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The Price of Being Poor, The Consumer Council, June 2011</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-